-- ── Galley ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Galley Solutions is a San Diego-based culinary resource planning (CRP) platform that centralizes recipe, menu, costing and allergen data for restaurants, foodservice operators and dietitians.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Custom$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Contact for pricing$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2017, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$11-50 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Diego, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Galley Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Galley Solutions is a San Diego culinary resource planning platform for recipes, costing and allergens. See features, pricing, pros, cons and rivals.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Galley Solutions is a San Diego-based software company that builds what it calls a Culinary Resource Planning, or CRP, platform: a system of record for recipes, menus, costs and nutrition data aimed at restaurants, catering companies, ghost kitchens, hospital and school foodservice operations, and other commercial kitchens. The company was founded in 2017 by Ian Christopher Brigden and Benji Koltai, and its core pitch is that most foodservice businesses run their culinary operations, including recipe development, menu costing, allergen labeling, purchasing and production planning, on a patchwork of spreadsheets, PDFs and disconnected point solutions, which makes it slow and error-prone to answer basic operational questions like the true food cost of a dish or which menu items contain a given allergen. Galley's platform centralizes that data in one place so chefs, operators and dietitians can all work from the same underlying recipe and ingredient records instead of maintaining separate, frequently out-of-sync copies. On the product side, Galley organizes its feature set around three constituencies. For chefs, it provides recipe management and scaling tools that let a dish be documented once and then automatically recalculated for different batch sizes, plating formats or menu contexts. For operators, it provides real-time costing that ties ingredient prices to recipes and menus so margin impact from a supplier price change is visible immediately rather than discovered at month-end reconciliation, along with purchasing, inventory and production-planning workflows. For dietitians and nutrition teams, a notable focus that distinguishes Galley from purely cost-focused kitchen software, it provides automated allergen tracking and nutrition-data tooling, particularly relevant for institutional foodservice operators such as hospital systems, school districts and senior living communities that face regulatory and liability requirements around allergen disclosure. The company reports its platform has been used to create more than 150,000 recipes and has supported the service of more than 5 million meals, and cites operators saving more than 45 hours of administrative work per week after adopting it, though these are company-reported figures rather than independently audited statistics. Galley has raised a total of roughly 20 million dollars in venture funding. The most significant disclosed round was a 14.2 million dollar Series A completed in May 2022, led by Astanor Ventures, a European investor focused on food and agriculture technology, with continued participation from earlier backer Zetta Venture Partners. This funding profile places Galley in the broader foodtech and restaurant-technology investment wave of the early 2020s, alongside adjacent categories like inventory management, food-waste reduction and kitchen automation software. Employee-count estimates vary by source, ranging from roughly 40 to over 60 people depending on the database consulted, consistent with a company operating at Series A or early-growth stage rather than a large enterprise vendor. Galley does not publish self-serve pricing tiers on its website; interested prospects are directed to book a demo or use a signup link tied to a sales conversation, typical for B2B software aimed at mid-market and enterprise foodservice operators rather than single-location independent restaurants. This is a meaningful contrast with lighter-weight, more self-serve competitors, and it signals that Galley's go-to-market is built around consultative sales and implementation support for organizations with more complex, multi-location or multi-brand culinary operations, the kind of customer for whom standardizing hundreds or thousands of recipes across kitchens is a significant, high-value operational project rather than a simple software purchase. The competitive set around Galley includes several categories of adjacent tools. Direct recipe-and-menu-costing competitors include Apicbase, a Belgium-based F and B management platform covering menu engineering, inventory and production; MarginEdge, which focuses heavily on invoice processing and real-time food cost tracking; and meez, a recipe and food-costing platform with a strong culinary-training angle. Broader restaurant back-office and inventory platforms such as CrunchTime and MarketMan compete for some of the same budget, particularly around purchasing and inventory control, though they tend to be less recipe-and-nutrition-centric than Galley. Waste-reduction-focused tools like Winnow occupy an adjacent but distinct niche. Galley's differentiation within this landscape rests on its recipe-first architecture, treating the recipe rather than the invoice or the inventory count as the central object that costing, allergen tracking and production planning all derive from, and on its explicit design for cross-functional use by chefs, operators and dietitians together, rather than serving primarily as a back-office finance tool. The realistic target audience for Galley is mid-size to large foodservice operations: multi-unit restaurant groups, catering and food-production companies, and institutional foodservice providers such as hospitals, universities, senior living and corporate dining that need to manage large, complex recipe libraries with real allergen and nutrition compliance requirements across many kitchens or locations. A single independent restaurant with one menu and one kitchen is less likely to be the ideal customer profile, both because of the platform's evident enterprise-sales orientation and because much of its value, standardizing recipe data across many cooks and locations, compounds with scale. Reviewers on platforms like Capterra rate the product highly, around 4.8 out of 5, consistent with a well-regarded, if narrower and more specialized, tool relative to broader restaurant-operations suites.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '81547fe6-0936-48d6-be6a-e999e7dcc1ec';

