-- ── Gameyfin ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Gameyfin is a free, open-source, self-hosted game library manager, often described as Jellyfin for games, that scans local game folders, fetches metadata and lets you browse, download and share your collection from a web interface.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2023, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Gameyfin Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Gameyfin is a free, open-source self-hosted game library manager, like Jellyfin for games. See features, setup, licensing and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Gameyfin is a free and open-source, self-hosted application for organizing and serving a personal video game library, frequently and accurately described by users and reviewers as Jellyfin for games. Just as Jellyfin, Plex or Emby let someone point a media server at a folder of movies and get back a browsable, metadata-rich library, Gameyfin points at folders containing PC game installers or files, sourced from platforms like Steam, Epic Games Store, GOG or a user's own backups, and automatically scans them, fetches cover art and metadata, and presents the result as a clean web interface that can be browsed and downloaded from any device on the network or, depending on configuration, remotely. The project is led by a developer using the handle grimsi and is developed in the open on GitHub under the gameyfin organization, with its first public releases dating to 2023; by mid-2026 the project had reached over 40 tagged releases and version 2.4.0, along with more than 1,000 GitHub stars, indicating a young but fast-moving and increasingly popular project within the self-hosting community. Technically, Gameyfin is built as a modern web application: the backend is written in Kotlin on top of Spring Boot 3, and the frontend combines Vaadin Hilla with React and TypeScript, backed by an embedded H2 database for simplicity of deployment. Extensibility is handled through the PF4J plugin framework, letting the community and the core team add new functionality, such as additional metadata providers, authentication methods or storage integrations, without modifying the core codebase. The project is distributed under the AGPL-3.0 licence, a copyleft licence that requires anyone who modifies Gameyfin and offers it as a network service to also release their modified source code, a common choice for self-hosted community software that wants to prevent commercial forks from closing off improvements. Feature-wise, beyond the core scan-and-serve functionality, Gameyfin supports direct in-browser downloads of games in the library, sharing a library with other users (useful for households or small friend groups pooling a game collection on a home server or NAS), LAN-aware caching so repeated downloads on a local network are fast, and accessibility-minded UI themes including colorblind-friendly options. Authentication is handled through single sign-on via OAuth2 and OpenID Connect, with documented support for self-hosted identity providers popular in the home-lab community such as Authentik and Pocket-ID, letting Gameyfin slot cleanly into an existing self-hosted authentication stack rather than requiring its own separate user database. Deployment is designed to be straightforward: the project ships official Docker images, is available as an app in Unraid's Community Applications store, and can otherwise run on any system with a Java Virtual Machine, giving it broad compatibility across Linux, Windows and macOS hosts commonly used for home servers. Because Gameyfin is entirely open source and, in the project's own words, 100 percent open source and free to use without any paywall, there is no pricing model, subscription or licensing fee to evaluate; the only cost to a user is the hardware they choose to run it on. This places Gameyfin squarely in the same category as other community-funded self-hosted projects rather than venture-backed SaaS, and its closest comparisons are other self-hosted library and media-server tools: Jellyfin and Plex for video, and Romm for game libraries specifically, alongside desktop-only front ends like LaunchBox and Playnite that are not server-based. Gameyfin's particular niche is combining Jellyfin-style server and client architecture, browse and download from any device via a browser rather than a single-machine desktop launcher, with the specific metadata and file-handling needs of PC game installers rather than video files. The target audience is PC gamers and home-lab enthusiasts who already run a self-hosted server, such as a NAS, home server, or small VPS, and want a Netflix-like or Jellyfin-like browsing experience for a personal or family game collection they legally own, rather than a way to acquire new games. It particularly appeals to privacy- and control-conscious users who prefer to manage their own game backups instead of relying solely on platform-specific cloud libraries, and to households that want to share one game collection across multiple family members' computers over a home network.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '615af08e-8dd3-4316-8837-e9ead4f24aa4';

