-- ── Garage ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Garage is a free, open-source, S3-compatible distributed object storage system built in Rust by the Deuxfleurs association, designed to run reliably across small, geographically distributed and even secondhand servers.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Distributed (Deuxfleurs association members based in Rennes, Paris, Lille and Brussels; registered address in Lille, France)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Garage Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Garage is a free, open-source S3-compatible object storage system for small, geo-distributed self-hosted clusters. See features and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Garage is a free and open-source, S3-compatible distributed object storage system built by Deuxfleurs, a French association of self-hosting enthusiasts and researchers. Where most S3-compatible storage software, including AWS S3 itself and self-hosted alternatives like MinIO, is designed to run inside a single, low-latency data center, Garage was designed from its very first release in 2020 for the opposite scenario: storage clusters made up of nodes running in different physical locations, sometimes with high inter-node network latency, sometimes on heterogeneous or secondhand hardware, and sometimes maintained by volunteers rather than a professional operations team. Deuxfleurs itself was founded by PhD students, including Alex Auvolat and Quentin Dufour, affiliated with Inria's WIDE research team studying distributed systems; Garage grew directly out of that research context and has been used in production by Deuxfleurs to run its own small-scale self-hosted services since its first release. The technical core of Garage combines two ideas from distributed-systems research: a Dynamo-style consistent hashing ring, in the tradition of Amazon's internal Dynamo system, to distribute data across nodes, and Conflict-Free Replicated Data Types (CRDTs) to reconcile state between nodes without requiring a consensus protocol like Raft. This is a deliberate architectural choice, since consensus protocols like Raft require a majority of nodes to agree before committing writes, which works well inside a single data center with low, predictable latency but degrades badly when nodes are spread across cities or countries with variable network conditions. By avoiding that consensus bottleneck, Garage lets every node handle read and write requests independently and reconcile eventual consistency afterward, which is what allows it to stay available and responsive even when some nodes are slow to reach or entirely unreachable, a property the project describes as being reliable enough to run outside datacenters. Garage is written in Rust and ships as a single, dependency-free static binary, keeping deployment simple: there is no external database, no separate metadata service and no complex orchestration layer required, and the project documents minimum requirements as low as 1GB of RAM, 16GB of disk and a CPU from the last decade (x86_64, ARMv7 or ARMv8), explicitly supporting the kind of secondhand or repurposed hardware that budget-constrained self-hosters and community tech collectives often run. On the API side, Garage implements the core of the Amazon S3 REST API, including multipart uploads for large files, presigned URLs, bucket policies, CORS configuration and object versioning. Because this is the same API surface used by Amazon S3 and other S3-compatible systems, existing tools and applications generally work with Garage without modification, including popular self-hosted software like Nextcloud for file storage, Matrix for chat media, Mastodon and PeerTube for federated social and video platforms, as well as generic S3 clients and backup tools like rclone, restic and Cyberduck. This compatibility is a major part of Garage's practical value: rather than asking developers to learn a new storage API, it lets them swap Garage in as a drop-in replacement for any part of their stack that already speaks S3. Garage is licensed under the GNU Affero General Public License v3 (AGPLv3), a strong copyleft licence that requires anyone who runs a modified version of Garage as a network service to publish their modifications, a common choice for infrastructure software built by non-commercial collectives that want to prevent proprietary forks. Unlike most tools in the comparable open-source infrastructure space, Garage's ongoing development has not been funded by venture capital or a company but primarily by European public research and internet-infrastructure funding programs: NGI POINTER, NLnet's NGI0 Entrust programme and the NGI0 Commons Fund all supported Garage's development between 2021 and 2025, reflecting the European Commission's Next Generation Internet initiative, which funds public-interest, non-commercial internet infrastructure projects. As an association rather than a company, Deuxfleurs does not report an employee count or a single headquarters in the conventional sense; its members are spread across several French and Belgian cities including Rennes, Paris, Lille and Brussels, with the association's formal registered address in Lille. Because there is no company selling Garage, there is no pricing model to describe beyond free; anyone can download and run it at zero licensing cost, with the only expense being whatever hardware they choose to run it on. Its closest competitors are other self-hostable object storage systems: MinIO is the most direct comparison and is far more widely deployed and commercially supported, including a paid enterprise tier, but is architected primarily for high-performance, low-latency, single-site or tightly-networked multi-site deployments rather than Garage's geo-distributed, high-latency-tolerant design; SeaweedFS and Ceph's RGW object gateway are other alternatives, generally aimed at larger-scale, more operationally complex deployments than Garage's small-to-medium sweet spot. Garage's realistic target audience is self-hosters, small non-profit and community tech collectives, and operators of federated services such as Mastodon instances, Matrix homeservers and small PeerTube instances, who need reliable, S3-compatible storage across a handful of low-cost or donated servers rather than a professionally managed data center footprint.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '3be3e9b4-cb50-43f7-9445-28dcf621ad49';

