-- ── Gatus ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Gatus is a developer-oriented health dashboard and status page tool, available as free self-hosted open-source software or as a managed cloud service at gatus.io, that monitors HTTP, TCP, DNS and other endpoints and alerts you when they fail.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted); paid plans at gatus.io$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Gatus Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Gatus is a free, open-source developer status page and health dashboard with 40+ alert integrations. See features, pricing and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Gatus is a developer-oriented health monitoring and status page tool that exists in two forms: a free, open-source, self-hosted project on GitHub, maintained primarily by a developer known by the handle TwiN, and a managed cloud version offered commercially at gatus.io for teams that would rather not operate their own monitoring infrastructure. The open-source project dates to 2019 and has grown into one of the more popular self-hosted monitoring tools in its category, with more than 10,000 GitHub stars and hundreds of forks by mid-2026. Unlike traditional application performance monitoring tools that passively observe real user traffic, Gatus takes an active-checking approach: it is configured with a list of endpoints, including HTTP and HTTPS URLs, TCP ports, DNS records, ICMP ping targets, WebSocket, gRPC, SSH connections, or TLS and STARTTLS certificates, and periodically probes each one, evaluating the result against a set of conditions the operator defines, such as an expected HTTP status code, a maximum response time, specific text in the response body, or a minimum number of days before a TLS certificate expires. When a condition fails, Gatus can trigger alerts through more than 40 built-in integrations, including Slack, Microsoft Teams, Discord, PagerDuty, Twilio for SMS and voice, Google Chat, Datadog, Splunk and generic custom webhooks, in addition to maintaining a public or internal status page and exporting metrics in Prometheus format for teams that already run a Grafana and Prometheus observability stack. The design philosophy behind Gatus is explicitly configuration as code: the entire monitoring setup, meaning which endpoints to check, how often, which conditions define health, and where alerts should go, lives in a single YAML file or a set of YAML files that Gatus automatically merges, with support for environment-variable interpolation so secrets like webhook URLs or API tokens do not need to be hardcoded. This stands in contrast to some competing tools, most notably Uptime Kuma, which emphasizes a fully point-and-click web UI for configuring checks; teams that prefer to version-control their monitoring configuration alongside their infrastructure-as-code workflows, such as Terraform, Kubernetes manifests, or GitOps pipelines, tend to gravitate toward Gatus's YAML-first model, while teams that want a non-technical staff member to add a check through a UI without touching a config file may prefer Uptime Kuma or a similar tool. Gatus supports several more advanced monitoring patterns beyond simple single-endpoint checks: Suites allow sequential, workflow-style checks useful for verifying a multi-step process like a login flow still works end to end, External Endpoints let agents running behind private networks or NAT push their status into a central Gatus instance rather than requiring Gatus to reach them directly, and Announcements let operators post incident updates directly on the public status page. Deployment options reflect Gatus's developer-first audience: official Docker images are published to both GitHub Container Registry and Docker Hub, a Helm chart is available for Kubernetes deployments, Terraform modules exist for infrastructure-as-code rollouts, and a plain compiled binary is available for teams that prefer to run it directly on a VM. Because Gatus has minimal runtime dependencies and can use lightweight storage backends, self-hosting costs are typically very low; community write-ups commonly cite running Gatus plus a small PostgreSQL database on platforms like Railway for around 2 to 5 dollars a month, which compares favorably to dedicated commercial status-page products like Better Uptime, whose plans commonly start around 29 dollars a month and often charge per monitored endpoint. This makes the self-hosted, Apache 2.0-licensed core of Gatus effectively free for unlimited endpoints and alert rules, with the operator's only real cost being their own server time and a small hosting bill. For organizations that want the Gatus experience without operating the underlying infrastructure themselves, gatus.io offers a managed, hosted version of the product: users can start exploring the dashboard for free and then move to a paid account tier to publish a live public status page and unlock additional account-level features, though gatus.io does not publish a fully itemized public rate card in the way some competitors do, so exact current pricing is best confirmed directly on the gatus.io pricing page at the time of purchase. This dual-track model, a genuinely free, unlimited, self-hostable open-source core plus an optional paid managed convenience layer, mirrors the strategy used by other successful open-source infrastructure projects and lets Gatus serve both budget-conscious self-hosters and teams that prioritize convenience over control. Gatus's direct competitors span both the self-hosted open-source space and the commercial SaaS space. In self-hosted, open-source monitoring, its closest peers are Uptime Kuma, with UI-first configuration and broad community adoption, and Upptime, a GitHub-Actions-based, git-native status page approach. In commercial SaaS status pages and uptime monitoring, it competes for budget with Statuspage from Atlassian, Better Uptime, Pingdom and UptimeRobot, though those tools generally charge per-monitor or per-seat fees that Gatus's self-hosted core avoids entirely. The realistic target audience is developers, DevOps and SRE teams who want infrastructure-as-code-style monitoring configuration, teams running Kubernetes or other container-orchestrated environments who want a lightweight status page that fits their existing GitOps workflow, and self-hosting hobbyists monitoring personal infrastructure who want a free alternative to paid uptime-monitoring SaaS.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'a647c355-aedc-4b4f-b8fd-c2ffd96f3b9a';

