-- ── Gem ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Gem is an AI-powered recruiting platform, often described as a Salesforce for hiring, that combines a sourcing CRM, applicant tracking, scheduling and analytics to help talent acquisition teams find, engage and hire candidates.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Custom$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$130/month (startup tier, 1-10 employees)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2017, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$150-500 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Gem Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Gem is an AI recruiting CRM and ATS platform used by 1,200+ talent teams. See 2026 pricing, features, pros, cons and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Gem is an AI-powered talent acquisition platform, commonly described in the market as 'a Salesforce for hiring' or 'a CRM for recruiting,' built to help talent acquisition teams source, engage, track and analyze candidates throughout the hiring process. This is the recruiting-software company at gem.com, headquartered in San Francisco, and should not be confused with an unrelated cryptocurrency and NFT company that also used the Gem name before being acquired by Blockdaemon; the two are entirely separate businesses. Gem the recruiting platform was founded in 2017 by Steven Bartel and Nick Bushak, both of whom had previously worked as engineering managers at Dropbox and Facebook, with Bartel currently serving as CEO. Their founding thesis was that recruiting teams, especially at fast-growing technology companies, lacked the kind of dedicated CRM tooling that sales teams had long taken for granted in products like Salesforce, and instead were forced to track sourcing and candidate relationships in spreadsheets or repurposed applicant tracking systems that were not built for proactive, high-volume outbound sourcing. Gem has raised a total of 148 million dollars in venture funding to date. The company's most significant and widely reported round was a 100 million dollar Series C completed in September 2021, led by ICONIQ Growth with continued participation from earlier investors Greylock Partners and Accel, plus new investors Sapphire Ventures and Meritech Capital; that round valued Gem at 1.2 billion dollars, making it a unicorn. Other investors associated with the company across its funding history include Cisco Investments, M12 (Microsoft's venture arm), Notable Capital, Team8, IBM Ventures and a number of individual angel investors. Employee-count estimates vary meaningfully by data source, ranging from roughly 150 to over 500, which likely reflects both genuine headcount changes over time and inconsistent methodology between data providers; a reasonable working estimate is a company in the low-to-mid hundreds of employees as of 2026. Functionally, Gem is built around four connected workflows. Sourcing and CRM tooling gives recruiters access to a database the company describes as covering more than 800 million professional profiles, combined with browser-based tools, including a well-known Chrome extension that integrates directly with LinkedIn Recruiter, that let sourcers save candidates, see engagement history, and launch personalized, multi-step outreach sequences across email without leaving the pages they are already browsing. Applicant tracking functionality covers job requisition management, structured application review, interview feedback collection and offer management, either as Gem's own native ATS or layered on top of an existing ATS like Greenhouse or Lever depending on which deployment model a customer chooses. Scheduling tools handle interview coordination, including a self-service candidate scheduling portal and automated interviewer load-balancing to spread interview volume evenly across a hiring panel. Analytics tools provide pipeline funnel dashboards, hiring forecasts and benchmarking data that let talent acquisition leaders compare their team's metrics, such as time-to-fill and source effectiveness, against industry data, an increasingly important selling point as recruiting organizations are asked to justify headcount and demonstrate return on investment to finance and executive stakeholders. More recently, Gem has layered AI agents on top of these workflows, including AI-assisted sourcing that suggests and ranks candidates, AI-assisted application review, and talent rediscovery features that resurface previously sourced or previously applied candidates who might fit a new opening, reducing the amount of cold, from-scratch sourcing a team needs to do for every new role. Gem's pricing is largely custom and quote-based, priced per seat and scaled to company size and deployment model, with two primary architectural choices offered to customers: Gem plus your ATS, where Gem operates as a sourcing and CRM layer that connects to an existing applicant tracking system, or Gem All-in-One, where Gem itself serves as the full ATS as well as the CRM. Within either model, Gem distinguishes between a Standard Seat, giving access to core sourcing, ATS workflows and candidate management, and an AI-Powered Seat, which unlocks the AI sourcing, application-review and candidate-ranking agents on top of the standard feature set, implying the more advanced AI functionality carries an additional per-seat cost. The one publicly disclosed pricing point is a startup-focused tier: companies with 1 to 10 full-time employees can access Gem's AI sourcing, CRM, analytics, scheduling and ATS functionality for 130 dollars per month, discounted from a standard rate of 270 dollars per month, with an additional 10 percent discount for annual billing; Gem also offers steeper startup incentives, including up to six months free followed by 50 percent off for companies under 30 employees, and reduced rates from day one for companies with 30 to 100 employees, reflecting a deliberate strategy of acquiring venture-backed startups early and growing revenue with them as they scale into larger, full-price enterprise customers. Gem serves more than 1,200 talent acquisition teams, with disclosed enterprise customers including Wayfair, Dropbox, Nasdaq, Cisco and DoorDash, positioning it firmly in the mid-market-to-enterprise segment of recruiting software rather than competing primarily on price with lightweight tools built for very small teams. Its most direct competitors are Ashby, a fast-growing challenger that bundles ATS, scheduling and analytics into a single modern product and is often discussed as a combined Greenhouse and Lever plus Gem replacement; the more established enterprise incumbents Greenhouse and Lever, which compete more on ATS process and compliance than on proactive sourcing; sourcing-focused rivals hireEZ and SeekOut, which compete most directly with Gem's CRM and AI-sourcing functionality; and Beamery, which positions itself more broadly as a Talent Lifecycle Management platform extending into workforce planning and internal mobility beyond pure recruiting CRM. Gem's differentiation within this set rests on its deep, long-standing LinkedIn, Gmail and Outlook workflow integration, its flexibility to sit alongside rather than replace an existing ATS, and its emphasis on recruiting analytics and benchmarking for talent acquisition leadership.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '3ade06e5-b645-47e5-8350-a2890ac101e4';

